Middle English <i>fore-man</i> ‘foreman, reeve’ (from the Old English prefix <i>fore-</i> ‘foremost’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’). The word is attested in this sense from the 15th century, but is not used specifically for the leader of a gang of workers before the late 16th century.","English: variant of <b>Fordman</b> with loss of <i>-d-</i>, from Middle English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ (Old English <i>ford</i>) + <i>man</i>, denoting either a dweller by or a keeper of a ford. Compare   Forder  .","Americanized form of German <b>Fohrmann</b> (see   Fohrman  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Fourman","meanings":["English: variant of   Forman   1 and 2."]},{"name":"Foreman","meanings":["English: variant of   Forman   1 and 2.","Altered form of North German <b>Formann</b>, a variant of   Fuhrmann   or   Fohrman  ."]},{"name":"Formanek","meanings":["Czech (<b>Formánek</b>): from a diminutive of   Forman  ."]},{"name":"Forder","meanings":["English: from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ (Old English <i>ford</i>), denoting either someone who lived near a ford or the keeper of a ford."]}]},{"name":"Dunstan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>dun</i> ‘dark’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’, borne most notably by a 10th-century saint who was archbishop of Canterbury. The name is now used mainly by Roman Catholics."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dunstan Forman was born about 1461, in Kent, England, his father, Sir Robert Foreman, was 27 and his mother, Jane Foreman, was 26. He had at least 2 sons. He died in 1492, in Brenchley, Kent, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1461–1492":"umbes 1461–1492","1461–1492":"1461–1492","1489–1527":"1489–1527","1486–1567":"1486–1567","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1437–Female":"1437–Surnud","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1567":"1567","1489":"1489","1486":"1486","1461":"1461","1492":"1492","1527":"1527","about